-        <section id="email-version-c">
-          <h1>Sovereign Deal Engine™</h1>
-
-          <!-- BLOCK 0 — Sovereign Engine Statement -->
-
-          <p>
-            The <strong>Sovereign Deal Engine™</strong> was built inside a
-            crisis — not to interpret the conflict, but to generate actionable
-            pathways out of it. It now stands at the heart of two distinct
-            frameworks: one to restore ethical balance, the other to reposition
-            strategic assets.
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            As a self-contained resolution system, it formalizes harm, encodes
-            alternatives, and activates pressure levers when traditional
-            governance fails.
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            Once the <strong>engine</strong> receives
-            <a href="./parameters.html" class="internal-link"
-              ><strong>conflict parameters</strong></a
-            >, it initiates a <strong>resolution instance</strong>. That
-            instance — here, the <em>Elite resolution instance</em> — generates
-            a <strong>narrative leverage output</strong>, used to encode
-            asymmetries and activate formal alternatives.
-          </p>
-
-          <p>
-            This <strong>artefact</strong> acts as a high-leverage signal. Based
-            on it, the instance formulates a
-            <strong>resolution contract request</strong>, addressed to the
-            <strong>HostAsset™</strong> — offering a structured path to a
-            <a href="#" class="note-link">potential exit</a>.
-          </p>
-          <p>
-            By default, the <strong>HostAsset™</strong> is considered an
-            operator of refusal. If no response is selected, a predetermined
-            sequence of events is executed —
-            <strong>closing the instance autonomously</strong>.
-          </p>
-          <hr />
-          <p>
-            These
-            <a href="./trigger.html" class="internal-link"
-              ><strong>triggers</strong></a
-            >
-            <u>along with the initial conflict parameters</u> — are formally
-            encoded into the engine as a <strong>sovereign input</strong>. They
-            are processed through a <strong>strategic decision layer</strong> —
-            pre-configured to detect avoidance signals. Any pattern of
-            <strong><em>refusal</em></strong
-            >, <strong><em>silence</em></strong
-            >, <strong><em>delay</em></strong
-            >, or <strong><em>misalignment</em></strong> triggers an
-            <u>automated path of resolution</u>, leading to a
-            <strong
-              ><u
-                >structured — and potentially irreversible — outcome</u
-              ></strong
-            >.
-          </p>
-
-          <!-- BLOCK 1 — Sovereign Input Contract Interface -->
-          <hr />
-
-          <p>
-            This strategic output is derived from a structured field immersion
-            (Nov–Dec 2024) within a hosted asset — <strong>QUAN</strong>, an F&B
-            operator located inside your Malmö premises. Signals captured
-            include board-level inconsistencies, operational opacity, and
-            ethical misalignment, culminating in an enforced dismissal under
-            <a href="predictable_conditions.html" class="note-link"
-              >predictable conditions</a
-            >.
-          </p>
-
-          <!-- BLOCK 2 — Strategic Output Notice -->
-
-          <!-- BLOCK 3 — Framework Presentation -->
-
-          <hr />
-          <section id="cloture-latente">
-            <p>
-              What can one realistically expect in terms of commitment — from a
-              'board professional' located in Geneva, managing a private banking
-              portfolio at Lombard Odier — or from his chairman alter ego, this
-              time residing in Sweden, yet holding six or seven mandates?
-            </p>
-
-            <p>
-              Let’s set aside what Bicky or Ingvar might have thought. We’ll
-              never know. What matters now is: Do you actually have a map of
-              material influences — or is this just a decorative board?
-            </p>
-            <p>
-              An asymmetrical ontological risk emerged — once dismissed as
-              noise, it now exposes the board itself as institutional risk where
-              the balance sheet feels like empty halls, echoing back the sound
-              of your own footsteps.
-            </p>
-
-            <p>
-              With nearly 1,000 employees, the absence of a visible Group CHRO
-              or CLO is no minor glitch. By contrast, Pandox maintains public
-              access to its board composition, organisational charts, and
-              strategic disclosures — all through a robust UX.
-            </p>
-          </section>
-          <p>
-            If such roles exist, they remain structurally invisible. If they
-            don’t — who carries the legal and human risk? The Conflict
-            Parameters section outlines how that absence enabled this breach to
-            unfold — and what emerged when no one owned the risk.
-          </p>
-          <hr />
-          <section class="ai-closure">
-            <p>
-              If you underestimate me again — as some within your own house once
-              did — I’ll go one step further, and make sure a good part of the
-              S&P 500 executive class remembers my playbook.
-            </p>
-
-            <p>
-              And if they remember my name, it won’t be as a genius, nor as a
-              threat,<br />
-              but as the first to wield
-              <strong>AI with strategic clarity</strong> — and to redraw the
-              lines.
-            </p>
-
-            <p>
-              If that unsettles you, it’s only because you haven’t grasped the
-              scale of what’s coming. Not me — but
-              <em>the wave I represent.</em>
-            </p>
-            <p>
-              If you think I’m dangerous, wait until it’s someone from the
-              inside — an overqualified, marginalised VP or regional manager, or
-              a CHRO ignored, a CLO sidelined — with a memory to settle and a
-              system to hack.
-            </p>
-          </section>
-          <p>Patrice Kenmoé</p>
